Main concerns expressed by the men were: “I want to see what my child is; some men think the abortion will break the woman’s uterus and to break up the family; what if the doctor may remove my child without a reason; abortion can spread sexually transmitted infections; continued promotion of contraception makes people get an impression that abortion is acceptable, and that government does nothing to stop this” (Mackenzie, 2013). Men and women in Tonga also believed that abortions could spread sexually transmitted infections including AIDs. Hence the Tonga MOH sees it fit to uphold a strict law on abortion.
2019] IMPLEMENTATION OF THE HUMAN RIGHTS IN TONGA 65 2. Legislations and other measures
2.1. Article 24 of the Constitution states that “every person shall have the right to life”, and “life shall be protected by law”.52 The common law judicial principle of fetophobia balances “fetal interests” against “maternal interests” as divergent to fetal and maternal rights. In particular, Smith v McGee (1983) was the first case in the Tongan courts to consider the right to life of a fetus.
